What is Moral Dumbfounding?

Moral Dilemmas

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21
  • Heinz

    • Is it wrong to steal a drug to save a loved one?/Is it wrong to demand profit from a life saving drug?

  • Trolley

    • Is it wrong to push someone off a bridge to save five?

  • Cannibal

    • Is it wrong to eat meat from a dead body?

  • Incest

    • Is it wrong for a brother and sister (Julie and Mark) to make love? (using contraception)

  • Have you got a reason for your Judgement?

Moral Dumbfounding: A Brief Overview

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21
  • Moral dumbfounding occurs when people
    • defend a moral judgement
    • even though they cannot provide supporting reasons
  • Manifests as:
    • Admissions of not having reasons
    • Use of
      • unsupported declarations (“it’s just wrong”) or
      • tautological reasons (“because it’s incest”)
  • Typically occurs for harmless taboos

(Haidt, 2001; Haidt, Björklund, & Murphy, 2000; McHugh, McGann, Igou, & Kinsella, 2017; Royzman, Kim, & Leeman, 2015)

Dumbfounded by Incest

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21

Influence of Moral Dumbfounding

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21
  • Moral Dumbfounding is cited as evidence for
    • intuitionist or dual-process theories of moral judgement
      • e.g., Crockett (2013); Cushman (2013); Greene (2008); Haidt (2001)
    • over more rationalist approaches
      • e.g., Kohlberg (1969); Topolski, Weaver, Martin, & McCoy (2013)


  • Its discovery (Haidt et al., 2000) coincided with
    • (and arguably contributed to)
    • the recent rise in intuitionist theories of moral judgements (Haidt, 2001)

Searching for Moral Dumbfounding

Background

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21
  • Haidt et al. (2000) widely discussed but:
    • unpublished manuscript (no peer review)
    • N = 30
    • No direct replication
    • Dumbfounding has been contested by some authors

      (e.g., Gray, Schein, & Ward, 2014; Guglielmo, 2018; Jacobson, 2012; Royzman et al., 2015; Sneddon, 2007; Wielenberg, 2014)

  • We conducted 3 studies:
    • Study 1: Interview - replication of Haidt et al. (2000)
    • Study 2: Computer task 1
    • Study 3: Computer task 2 (college sample: 3a; MTurk Sample: 3b)

Searching: Study 1: Method

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21

Participants:

  • 31 participants (MIC/UL students and alumni)

    (15 female, 16 male, 0 other; Mage = 28.83, min = 19, max = 64, SD = 10.99)

Procedure:

  • Participants presented with 4 scenarios and asked to judge the behaviour of the characters in the scenarios (Heinz, Cannibal, Incest, Trolley)
  • The Experimenter challenged the judgement
  • Responses of interest:
    • Admissions of not having reasons
    • Unsupported declarations

(McHugh et al., 2017)

Searching: Study 1: Coded Videos

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21
  • Analysis revealed significant differences in:
    • Laughing
    • Smiling
    • Silence
  • No differences in:
    • verbal hesitations; non-verbal hesitations
    • changing posture; fidgeting/hands on the self
    • frowning
  • No difference depending on which measure of dumbfounding was used (Admissions of not having reasons / Unsupported declarations)

Responding to Criticisms: The role of Principles

Criticisms of Moral Dumbfounding

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21

  • Critics suggest dumbfounding is a non-phenomenon

  • Failure to provide reasons does not mean there are no reasons (Sneddon, 2007)

  • People implicitly perceive harm (Gray et al., 2014)

  • People have do have reasons but are “beaten into submission” (Jacobson, 2012)

  • Evidence for principles or reasons guiding judgements (Royzman et al., 2015)

Evidence for Principles Guiding Judgements

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21
  • Royzman, Kim, and Leeman (2015) identified two principles that appear to be guiding judgements
  • The Harm Principle
  • The Norm Principle
  • Participants who endorse either principle have a reason to judge the behaviour of Julie and Mark as wrong

Understanding Moral Dumbfounding

Dual-processes / Dual-systems

(taken from Thaler & Sunstein, 2008, p. 20)

Dual-Processes and Moral Dumbfounding

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21

  • Dual-process theories of moral judgement

  • Conflict in dual-process occurs when

    • a habitual (System 1) response is different
    • from a response that results from deliberation (System 2)


  • Three response options in the dumbfounding paradigm
    • It’s wrong and I can provide a valid reason
    • It’s wrong but I can’t think of a reason
    • There is nothing wrong (competing intuitions)

(Crockett, 2013; Cushman, 2013; Evans, 2007; Evans & Stanovich, 2013; Greene, 2008)

Cognitive Load and Moral Dumbfounding

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21

  • Manipulations of Cognitive load are known to inhibit deliberative responding

  • Recall the three response options in dumbfounding

    • (a) It’s wrong and I can provide a valid reason
    • (b) It’s wrong but I can’t think of a reason
    • (c) There is nothing wrong (competing intuitions)

Cognitive load & dumbfounded responding

↓ ↓ ↓ ↓            Giving reasons (a)              ↓ ↓ ↓ ↓

↑    ↑     Dumbfounded responding (b)     ↑ ↑ ↑

↑    ↑     There is nothing wrong (c)            ↑

Individual Differences in Moral Dumbfounding

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21

  • Dumbfounded responding may be linked with individual differences

  • Need for Cognition has been linked to dual-process approaches to cognition

  • The Need for Cognition Scale (NFC) is a measure of an individual’s tendency

                “to engage in and enjoy effortful analytic activity”

                                                        (Forsterlee & Ho, 1999, p. 471; see also Cacioppo & Petty, 1982)

  • tendency to engage in deliberation
  • a person’s need to understand and make sense of the world

(Cacioppo & Petty, 1982; Evans & Stanovich, 2013; Forsterlee & Ho, 1999; Petty, Cacioppo, & Kao, 1984; Petty, Feinstein, Blair, & Jarvis, 1996)

Individual Differences in Moral Dumbfounding

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21

We hypothesised:

  • People who score highly on the NFC
    • will be more likely to provide reasons for their judgement
  • People who score low on the NFC
    • are likely to fail to identify reasons for their judgement
  • NFC is related to a need to understand and make sense of the world
    • Of the people who fail to identify reasons for their judgement:
      • those who revise their judgement will likely score higher on the NFC than people who provide a dumbfounded response

Cognitive Load Control
Nothing Wrong 1.92 -1.92
Dumbfounded 2.75* -2.75*
Reason -3.86** 3.86**

Note: * = sig. at p < .05 ( |z| > 1.96); ** = sig. at p < .001 ( |z| > 3.3)

  • χ2(2, N = 626) = 15.302, p < .001, V = 0.16, the observed power was 0.95

Cognitive Load and Dumbfounded Responding

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21
  • A mini meta-analysis found that cognitive load significantly influenced responding across all studies
    • χ2(10) = 26.882, p = .003 (Fisher’s method)
    • when weighting for sample size, z = 2.874, p = .002 (Stouffer’s Z-score method)

Cognitive Load and Dumbfounded Responding

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21

Need for Cognition

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21
  • Significant association between Need for Cognition and response to the critical slide
    • χ2(2, N = 654) = 12.15, p = .002, The observed power was 0.89.
  • Need for Cognition explained between 0.48% (Cox and Snell R square) and 0.72% (Nadelkerke R squared) of the variance in responses to the critical slide.
  • As Need for Cognition increased, participants were significantly more likely to provide reasons than to present as dumbfounded:
    • Wald = 11.01, p < .001, odds ratio = 1.27, 95% CI [1.1, 1.46]
  • As Need for Cognition increased, participants were also significantly more likely to select there is nothing wrong than present as dumbfounded Wald = 7.86, p = .005, odds ratio = 1.27, 95% CI [1.07, 1.5].

Conclusion

Conclusion

Cillian McHugh - 24/6/21


  • People cannot always provide reasons for their moral judgements


  • Dumbfounding occurs for a range of scenarios, and in diverse samples


  • Further research is required to understand the mechanisms that lead to moral dumbfounding
